## JavaScript Debounce Function

A debounce function delays executing a function until after a specified wait time has elapsed since the last time it was called.

```javascript
// Debounce function
function debounce(fn, delay) {
  let timer;
  return function (...args) {
    clearTimeout(timer);
    timer = setTimeout(() => fn.apply(this, args), delay);
  };
}

// --- Example Usage ---

// A function that simulates a search API call
function searchAPI(query) {
  console.log(`Searching for: "${query}"`);
}

// Wrap it with debounce — only fires 300ms after the user stops typing
const debouncedSearch = debounce(searchAPI, 300);

// Simulating rapid keystrokes (e.g., user typing "hello")
debouncedSearch("h");
debouncedSearch("he");
debouncedSearch("hel");
debouncedSearch("hell");
debouncedSearch("hello");

// Output (only once, after 300ms of inactivity):
// Searching for: "hello"
```

### How it works

| Step | What happens |
|------|-------------|
| Called | Clears any existing timer |
| Waiting | Starts a new `setTimeout` |
| Called again | Resets the timer (repeat) |
| Idle for `delay`ms | Timer fires, function executes |

> **Common use cases:** search inputs, window resize handlers, and form validation.
